```

The Doppler comparison is the clearest support diagnostic. When the true
signal crosses zero, the one-sided fit cannot represent its negative portion by
construction. This is correct behavior under the specified prior, not a
numerical failure.

# Learned state centers and ash mixtures

The fitted center, occupancy, self-transition probability, and point-component
weight reveal how each HMM state is being used.

```{r state-table-helper}
state_table <- function(fit) {
  data.frame(
    state = seq_along(fit$fitted$mu),
    center = fit$fitted$mu,
    occupancy = fit$fitted$state_occupancy,
    self_transition = diag(fit$fitted$transition),
    point_component_weight = fit$fitted$mixture_weight[, 1],
    row.names = NULL
  )
}

primary_fit <- function(signal_name) {
  # Use signed support when the benchmark truth genuinely crosses zero.
  if (!is.null(signed) && any(truth[[signal_name]] < 0)) {
    signed[[signal_name]]$fit
  } else {
    one_sided[[signal_name]]$fit
  }
}
```

```{r learned-states, results='asis'}
for (name in names(truth)) {
  cat("\n\n###", tools::toTitleCase(name), "\n\n")
  print(knitr::kable(state_table(primary_fit(name)), digits = 4))
}
```

The rows of `fit$fitted$mixture_weight` are the separately learned ash priors.
The heat maps below display their mass across the fixed scale grid. State
labels on the vertical axis give the learned centers.

```{r mixture-heatmap-helper}
plot_mixture_heatmap <- function(fit, main = "State-specific ash mixtures") {
  rho <- fit$fitted$mixture_weight
  scales <- fit$fitted$prior_sd
  centers <- fit$fitted$mu

  if (nrow(rho) == 1L) {
    barplot(
      as.numeric(rho),
      names.arg = signif(scales, 3),
      xlab = "ash prior scale",
      ylab = "mixture weight",
      main = main,
      col = "firebrick3",
      border = NA
    )
    return(invisible(NULL))
  }

  if (ncol(rho) == 1L) {
    barplot(
      as.numeric(rho),
      names.arg = signif(centers, 3),
      xlab = "state center",
      ylab = "mixture weight",
      main = main,
      col = "firebrick3",
      border = NA
    )
    return(invisible(NULL))
  }

  image(
    x = seq_len(ncol(rho)),
    y = seq_len(nrow(rho)),
    z = t(rho),
    axes = FALSE,
    xlab = "ash prior scale",
    ylab = "state center",
    main = main,
    col = grDevices::hcl.colors(40, "YlOrRd", rev = TRUE)
  )
  x_at <- unique(round(seq(1, ncol(rho), length.out = min(8, ncol(rho)))))
  y_at <- unique(round(seq(1, nrow(rho), length.out = min(12, nrow(rho)))))
  axis(1, at = x_at, labels = signif(scales[x_at], 3), las = 2, cex.axis = 0.75)
  axis(2, at = y_at, labels = signif(centers[y_at], 3), las = 2, cex.axis = 0.75)
  box()
}
```

```{r mixture-heatmaps, fig.height=8}
old_par <- par(mfrow = c(3, 1), mar = c(5, 5, 2, 2))
for (name in names(truth)) {
  fit <- primary_fit(name)
  plot_mixture_heatmap(
    fit,
    main = paste(tools::toTitleCase(name), "state-specific mixtures")
  )
}
par(old_par)
```

A high weight in the first column means that the state behaves approximately
like a flat point level at its learned center. Diffuse mass across positive
scales permits within-state effect variation.

# State pruning and selected steps

`pruning_history` distinguishes states removed during dynamic reduction from
states excluded by the initial independent prefilter. `step_selection` is a
separate change-penalized decoder and directly reports contiguous segments.

```{r pruning-and-steps, results='asis'}
for (name in names(truth)) {
  fit <- primary_fit(name)
  cat("\n\n###", tools::toTitleCase(name), "\n\n")

  initial_kept <- fit$grid$initial_selected_index %||%
    fit$grid$selected_index %||% seq_along(fit$grid$full_mu)
  removed_before_hmm <- length(fit$grid$full_mu) - length(initial_kept)
  dynamically_pruned <- nrow(fit$pruning_history %||% data.frame())
  cat(
    "Candidates removed from the original grid:", removed_before_hmm,
    "  \nDynamically pruned records:", dynamically_pruned,
    "  \nDecoded steps:", fit$step_selection$step_count,
    "  \nDecoded changes:", fit$step_selection$change_count,
    "\n\n"
  )

  segments <- fit$step_selection$segments
  if (nrow(segments)) {
    print(knitr::kable(utils::head(segments, 20), digits = 4))
    if (nrow(segments) > 20) {
      cat("\nOnly the first 20 decoded segments are displayed.\n")
    }
  }
}
```

# Practical recommendations

1. Use `nonnegative_state_means = TRUE` when negative latent effects are
   scientifically impossible. This is the current default.
2. Use `nonnegative_state_means = FALSE` for signed waveforms such as Doppler
   or log-fold changes whose sign is meaningful.
3. Keep `shared_mixture = FALSE` when distinct states should learn different
   degrees of within-state variation.
4. Use `null_state = "pointmass"` when zero is a scientifically exact null.
   Use an adaptive null only when small positive effects should be absorbed by
   the zero-centered state.
5. Inspect `fit$fitted$mu`, `fit$fitted$mixture_weight`,
   `fit$fitted$state_occupancy`, `fit$pruning_history`, and
   `fit$step_selection`; a posterior-mean plot alone does not diagnose the
   fitted HMM.
6. Do not compare the fitted HMM likelihoods of the signed and truncated models
   as if they had identical supports. Choose the support primarily from the
   scientific meaning of the latent effect.

